    "body": "> besides using debug_tracetransaction?\r\n\r\nYou can't, afaik. \r\n\r\n> But using this way will cost a lot of resources and time.\r\n\r\nYeah, the thing is, there is _no way_ to obtain internal transactions cheaply. It is an intrinsically non-trivial problem, since geth does not store any such metadata about transactions - so each transaction must be (re-)executed in order to see what internal transactions are made. \r\n\r\n\r\n> a specific tracer to capture the \"ether transfer\"(we don't have it now)?\r\n\r\nI think that would be more or less very similar to the existing callTracer? Anyway, I think such a tracer would only solve ~60% of the usecases, since most people are also interested in token/nft transfers, not only ether. ",
